# Backend Security

## Purpose

This rule defines mandatory security practices for the FastAPI backend: authentication, authorization, input hardening, secret protection, and PCI-aware payment handling.

Security is not optional. Every endpoint and use case must fail closed when identity or permissions are uncertain.

---

## Scope

Applies to:

- Authentication dependencies in `apps/api/core/security/`
- Authorization policies in feature application layers
- Password hashing, JWT/session handling, API keys
- CORS, security headers, rate limiting middleware
- Webhook signature verification (Stripe, etc.)
- Input sanitization and SSRF-safe outbound calls
- PCI scope minimization for payment flows

Does not apply to:

- Frontend XSS prevention (web app rules)
- WAF/CDN configuration
- Organization-wide IAM policies
- Penetration test execution

---

## Core Principles

Always:

- Authenticate before authorization; authorize every mutating and sensitive read operation
- Use established libraries: `passlib`/argon2, `python-jose` or equivalent for JWT, official SDK signature verification
- Store password hashes with strong algorithms (Argon2id or bcrypt); never plaintext or reversible encryption
- Validate webhook signatures before processing payload
- Apply least privilege to service accounts and DB roles
- Parameterize all SQL via SQLAlchemy; never string-concatenate user input into queries
- Use HTTPS-only cookies with `HttpOnly`, `Secure`, `SameSite` when cookie auth applies
- Rate limit login, password reset, checkout, and webhook endpoints
- Keep cardholder data out of application logs and databases (Stripe Elements / tokenization)

Never:

- Trust client-supplied user ids or roles without server verification
- Expose internal stack traces or schema details in production errors
- Disable auth for "temporary" debugging in committed code
- Store CVV, full track data, or PIN
- Run production with default secrets or `debug=True`
- Bypass authorization in "admin shortcut" endpoints

---

## Authentication

Location: `apps/api/core/security/auth.py`

- FastAPI `Depends(get_current_user)` validates token/session on protected routes
- Separate optional auth dependency for public endpoints with enhanced features when logged in
- Token expiry, refresh rotation, and revocation strategy documented
- Service-to-service auth via mTLS or signed tokens where applicable

JWT guidelines:

- Short-lived access tokens
- Sign with strong secret or asymmetric keys from settings (`SecretStr`)
- Validate `aud`, `iss`, `exp` claims

---

## Authorization

Location: `apps/api/app/features/<feature>/application/policies/`

- Policy methods: `can_cancel_order(user, order) -> bool`
- Checked in Application layer before domain mutation
- Role-based + resource-based rules explicit; no magic role strings scattered in routers

Fail closed: if policy cannot decide → deny.

---

## Input and Output Safety

- Pydantic validates all inbound data
- Bound string lengths and collection sizes on list endpoints
- Reject unexpected fields when strict mode warranted
- Serialize responses through response models; do not return raw dicts from ORM
- File uploads: validate content type, size limits, store outside web root, scan if policy requires

---

## Webhooks (Payments)

For Stripe and similar:

- Verify signature with raw body and endpoint secret
- Enqueue processing idempotently; respond quickly with 2xx after persistence to outbox
- Never trust client-side payment success without webhook or server-side confirmation

See skills: `stripe-integration`, `pci-compliance`, `payment-integration`.

---

## Secrets and Configuration

- Secrets only via settings (`10-configuration`)
- Rotate keys without code deploy when platform supports
- Separate DB credentials per environment

---

## Decision Rules

IF endpoint mutates data or reads private user data
THEN require authentication and authorization policy.

IF receiving third-party webhook
THEN verify signature before any business logic.

IF handling payment
THEN use provider tokenization; PCI scope stays with provider-hosted fields.

IF calling external URL from user-provided input
THEN block private IP ranges (SSRF guard) or disallow user-controlled URLs.

IF error message might reveal resource existence to attacker
THEN use consistent 404/403 policy (see `04-error-handling`).

IF brute-force risk (login, coupon codes)
THEN rate limit and audit failures.

---

## Anti-Patterns

Never create:

- `@router.get("/admin/users")` without auth because "it's internal"
- Hardcoded API keys in repository
- SQL built with f-strings from query params
- Logging Authorization headers or payment payloads
- CORS `allow_origins=["*"]` with credentials in production
- Custom crypto for passwords or tokens
- Trusting `X-User-Id` header from client

---

## Validation Checklist

Before shipping backend changes verify:

✓ Protected routes use auth dependencies.

✓ Authorization policy enforced in application layer.

✓ Webhooks verify signatures.

✓ No secrets in code or logs.

✓ SQL injection prevented via ORM/parameters.

✓ Rate limiting on sensitive endpoints.

✓ PCI scope minimized for payments.

✓ Security headers and CORS configured for environment.

✓ Dependencies scanned for known vulnerabilities.

✓ Security tests cover authz bypass attempts.

